Since $\triangle AHF \sim \triangle CHE$, we have $\frac{AH}{CH} = \frac{AF}{CE}$.  Since $AF = \frac{1}{3}AB$ and $CE = \frac{1}{2}DC = \frac{35}{AB}$, we have
\[\frac{AH}{CH} = \frac{\frac{1}{3}AB}{\frac{35}{AB}} = \frac{AB^2}{105}.\]Since $\triangle AJG \sim \triangle CJH$, we have $\frac{AJ}{CJ} = \frac{AG}{CE}$.  Since $AG = \frac{2}{3}AB$ and $CE = \frac{35}{AB}$, we have
\[\frac{AJ}{CJ} = \frac{\frac{2}{3}AB}{\frac{35}{AB}} = \frac{2AB^2}{105}.\]Therefore,
\[\frac{AH + AJ}{CH + CJ} = \frac{\frac{AB^2}{105} + \frac{2AB^2}{105}}{\frac{35}{AB}} = \frac{3AB^3}{3675} = \frac{AB^3}{1225}.\]Since $AH + AJ = AC$ and $CH + CJ = AC$, we have $\frac{AC}{AC} = \frac{AB^3}{1225}$, so $AB^3 = 1225$.  Then $AB = 5\sqrt{5}$, so $DC = \frac{70}{5\sqrt{5}} = 14\sqrt{5}$.

